<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp1sec1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The algebra of the integers</title>

  <p>To begin, the integers have certain well-known algebraic properties.  These properties can be summarized by saying that the integers form a <term>commutative ring with identity</term>.</p>

  <definition xml:id="definition-commutative_ring">
    <title>Commutative Ring with Identity</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A <term>commutative ring with identity</term> is a set <m>R</m> with two binary operations: 
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  an addition operation <m>+</m> and a
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                 <p>
                  multiplication operation <m>\cdot</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
            satisfying 7 axioms:
            <dl width="narrow">
              <li><title>(R1)</title>
                <p>
                  (Addition is <term>associative</term>.) If <m>a,b,c \in R</m>, then <m>(a+b)+c=a+(b+c)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R2)</title>
                <p>
                  (Addition has an <term>identity</term>.) There exists an element <m>0 \in R</m> with the property that, if <m>a \in R</m>, then <m>0+a=a</m>.  We call <m>0</m> a <term>zero</term>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R3)</title>
                <p>
                  (Addition has <term>inverses</term>.) If <m>a \in R</m>, then there exists an element <m>-a \in R</m> so that <m>a+(-a)=0</m>.  We call <m>-a</m> an <term>additive inverse</term> to <m>a</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R4)</title>
                <p>
                  (Addition is <term>commutative</term>.) If <m>a,b\in R</m>, then <m>a+b=(b+a)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R5)</title>
                <p>
                  (Multiplication is <term>associative</term>.) If <m>a,b,c \in R</m>, then <m>(ab)c=a(bc)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R6)</title>
                <p>
                  (Multiplication has an <term>identity</term>.) There exists an element <m>1 \in R</m> with the property that, if <m>a \in R</m>, then <m>1a=a</m>.  We call <m>1</m> a <term>one</term>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li><title>(R7)</title>
                <p>
                  (Multiplication <term>distributes</term> across addition.) If <m>a, b, c \in R</m>, then <m>a(b+c)=ab+ac</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    <alert>Nontriviality assumption:</alert> We assume that the ring <m>R</m> is nontrivial, i.e., <m>0 \ne 1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>We will establish some basic properties of commutative rings with identity in the following propositions.</p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-1_1-01">
  <title>s</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with identity and <m>a \in R</m>, then <m>0a=0</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof. Analyze the sum <m>a0+a0</m>.  You may find ring properties (R7), (R2), and (R3) in <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-1_1-02">
  <title>s</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>R</m> is a commutative ring with identity, and <m>a \in R</m> <m>(-1)a=-a</m>.  
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof. Analyze the sum <m>(1)a+(-1)a</m>. You may find <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/> and <xref ref="prop-1_1-01"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<p>
  Both operations of addition and multiplication have a notion of inverse, however we are only guaranteed to have additive inverses.  We will say an element <m>a \in R</m> is <term>multiplicatively invertible</term> if it has a multiplicative inverse, i.e. if there exists an element <m>b \in R</m> such that <m>ab=1</m>.   When it is clear from context, we will simply say <m>a</m> is <term>invertible</term>, or that <m>a</m> is a <term>unit</term>.
</p>  
</section>